What This Means — Skills Expected of a PCPP1 Candidate

Someone aiming for PCPPIf you like — I can pull up a full PCPP1 syllabus PDF (or a markdown-checklist version) for you — many people find that useful — do you want me to build it with the sub-sub-topics (e.g. GUI → widgets, layout, events; File I/O → csv, xml, logging, config)?1 should be comfortable beyond basic Python: they should be able to

design and implement classes and OOP-based architectures, potentially using special / magic methods for custom behavior,

write Python code following community-standard style and conventions (PEP 8 / PEP 257 / PEP 20), for readability and maintainability,

build basic GUI applications, using a toolkit like tkinter, with events, widgets, layout managers, etc.,

write network-aware Python programs: communicate via sockets or HTTP, send/receive JSON or XML, understand RESTful concepts, integrate with web services or APIs,

store, read, write, and manage data — from databases (SQLite), flat files (CSV, XML), configs, and log files — enabling them to build “real-world” applications that persist data and handle I/O.

In short: instead of being limited to writing scripts, a PCPP1-certified programmer should be able to build medium-sized, maintainable applications with GUI, data persistence, network communication, and correct structure + style.

